1
00:00:00,750 --> 00:00:02,330
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,770 --> 00:00:11,350
Today we'll be looking at how this amplifier attachment for the lab signal generator works for testing our coils.

3
00:00:12,230 --> 00:00:13,730
There's nothing complicated about it.

4
00:00:15,390 --> 00:00:31,930
It's built around an IRF840 transistor, with a TC4420 driver for that transistor on the heat sink, and a go-between chip linking the lab signal generator and the driver.

5
00:00:32,070 --> 00:00:37,750
The go-between chip is the same one as before — a TC4093BP.

6
00:00:39,350 --> 00:00:48,750
To power these chips we use a DC-DC converter built around the LM2596.

7
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:56,410
We set it to 15 V with the trim pot and feed it a slightly higher voltage.

8
00:00:56,650 --> 00:01:00,730
In my case it's an 18 V mains converter.

9
00:01:01,670 --> 00:01:04,290
It can run from batteries too — whatever you have on hand.

10
00:01:05,410 --> 00:01:10,050
The schematic is shown in the picture.

11
00:01:10,570 --> 00:01:18,970
By the way, I'll upload all my schematics to a file-sharing service and drop the link under this video — same as the one I filmed before.

12
00:01:20,490 --> 00:01:26,730
At this point you should see a nice clean oscillogram like this.

13
00:01:27,950 --> 00:01:30,010
Let's see what else.

14
00:01:30,450 --> 00:01:44,350
The signal from the lab signal generator hits one of the Schmitt triggers, gets inverted, and then we invert it again on the second Schmitt trigger to get the true signal.

15
00:01:44,410 --> 00:01:53,050
From there, through a 10 Ω damping resistor, the signal reaches the driver controlling the FET's gate.

16
00:01:53,970 --> 00:02:09,530
Then the FET switches our main power — from batteries or any other power source — onto the inductor that drives our coil.

17
00:02:11,930 --> 00:02:18,910
The wiring isn't complicated. Let's look at how it works.

18
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:25,730
First, this system connects to the lab signal generator.

19
00:02:26,590 --> 00:02:37,870
The lab generator gets switched to pulse mode, then you set the pulse frequency on the control.

20
00:02:38,550 --> 00:02:48,950
Our circuit works up to 2.5 MHz. After that, we set the signal amplitude.

21
00:02:49,090 --> 00:02:56,670
Signal amplitude is 6 volts — that's the minimum this attachment will work at.

22
00:02:57,290 --> 00:03:05,890
If you have a 5-volt signal generator, you'll need to swap this Schmitt trigger chip for 5-volt logic.

23
00:03:06,050 --> 00:03:11,730
It's also compatible with this driver.

24
00:03:12,090 --> 00:03:22,110
You'd just need to add an L7805 regulator after this converter for the 5-volt logic supply.

25
00:03:23,190 --> 00:03:25,250
And the circuit will work just fine.

26
00:03:27,510 --> 00:03:31,630
Once the amplitude is set, the next thing is the duty cycle.

27
00:03:31,750 --> 00:03:34,670
Right now duty cycle is at 73%.

28
00:03:34,670 --> 00:03:36,770
Let me show you what the duty cycle does.

29
00:03:37,490 --> 00:03:43,530
I feed power from the supply to the transistor.

30
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:51,940
We see the oscillogram.

31
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:56,080
This is what you should get.

32
00:03:57,360 --> 00:04:00,400
Now watch — I'm going to change the duty cycle.

33
00:04:00,740 --> 00:04:03,460
In this case, decreasing it.

34
00:04:04,620 --> 00:04:09,380
See — the signal becomes unclean.

35
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:22,740
So for each coil we have to dial in the signal individually, along with the transistor's operating point at that frequency.

36
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:25,260
That's the duty cycle adjustment.

37
00:04:25,780 --> 00:04:27,980
Here I dropped it to 10%.

38
00:04:27,980 --> 00:04:31,740
Bringing it back to a clean signal.

39
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:40,560
In this case at this frequency, it starts working around 71%.

40
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:48,240
Once we've got a clean signal, we start probing our coil.

41
00:04:49,920 --> 00:04:51,000
What do we get?

42
00:04:51,320 --> 00:05:07,900
With this kind of drive, with the LC resonance frequency for this coil set at 1.68 MHz, the coils start behaving just like a Tesla coil.

43
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:17,620
Right now both ends are in the air, it's not grounded, and you can see there's a discharge —

44
00:05:21,630 --> 00:05:24,490
basically the same kind of corona as a Tesla.

45
00:05:33,960 --> 00:05:41,840
The coil's working in quarter-wave mode — you can tell by how the neon bulb glows.

46
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:45,760
Closer to the hot end the glow gets brighter.

47
00:05:46,900 --> 00:05:58,660
There's a fluorescent tube parallel to the coil — to light it up, we touch the hot end to its lead.

48
00:05:59,620 --> 00:06:04,840
I touched the hot end to it and you can see the lamp lights up brightly.

49
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:08,280
After disconnecting, the lamp glows dimly.

50
00:06:09,660 --> 00:06:12,100
And what should we see on this lamp?

51
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:22,400
The camera might not pick it up, but there are stripes running along the lamp — the whole tube goes striped.

52
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:39,120
And if the coil is wound correctly, those stripes will be sharply defined. You want to find the frequency on the lab signal generator where the stripes stop moving entirely.

53
00:06:39,720 --> 00:06:43,780
If that happens, the coil is properly built.

54
00:06:43,780 --> 00:07:04,580
If you can't get the stripes to stop by changing the frequency, and they keep moving, then the coil is wound slightly wrong — you're not getting a clean longitudinal standing wave around the coil.

55
00:07:04,580 --> 00:07:06,020
Around this coil.

56
00:07:06,780 --> 00:07:17,600
You'd need to tweak it — either increase or decrease the wire length. That's a matter of trial and error.

57
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:37,200
But the main goal is for the coil to start up and behave like a Tesla transformer — the neons and gas-discharge lamps should light up, and most importantly, you want to see those stripes on the lamp.

58
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:40,300
The signal again.

59
00:07:42,680 --> 00:07:46,100
I already showed how to set it.

60
00:07:46,860 --> 00:07:48,300
And the current draw at this point.

61
00:07:50,500 --> 00:07:54,260
1.32 amps at 12.4 volts.

62
00:07:55,300 --> 00:08:05,300
The better the coil is wound, the less input power it needs, and the brighter the lamp lights up.

63
00:08:06,680 --> 00:08:13,620
The lamp also glows brighter if we connect grounding to this coil.

64
00:08:14,220 --> 00:08:21,420
Watch — I connect grounding, and you can see the brightness increase.

65
00:08:25,060 --> 00:08:27,060
Without changing the power.

66
00:08:29,020 --> 00:08:35,220
We can take a look with the second probe to see what's going on.

67
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:37,160
I'll place it next to the coil.

68
00:08:44,260 --> 00:08:46,800
Let's see what we have on the coil.

69
00:08:47,020 --> 00:08:50,460
On the coil at this frequency we have a sine wave.

70
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:56,920
On the sine wave you can clearly see the kick from the pulse.

71
00:08:58,620 --> 00:08:59,580
A sharp little bump.

72
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:06,800
Now let's try changing the lab generator frequency.

73
00:09:08,120 --> 00:09:10,200
I'm changing the frequency, going lower.

74
00:09:10,980 --> 00:09:12,320
Here's a characteristic feature.

75
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:29,140
If the coil absorbs your signal well — that is, if it's well matched in frequency — the peaks on the inductor will decrease in amplitude.

76
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:39,620
Watch — I detune the system, the peak grows, and the amplitude on the coil itself drops.

77
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:43,420
That's a sign you're at the wrong frequency.

78
00:09:45,860 --> 00:09:54,840
Bringing it back — and we'll get the same picture if we go higher in frequency.

79
00:09:57,680 --> 00:10:02,740
Same thing — peak grows, signal drops.

80
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:15,320
We aim for maximum amplitude on the coil and maximum glow from the lamps around it.

81
00:10:15,620 --> 00:10:20,480
But most importantly, again, those stripes on the lamp.

82
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:24,680
When you see them, they'll be running around chaotically.

83
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:28,100
The camera just doesn't pick it up — they're running right now.

84
00:10:28,780 --> 00:10:30,400
The eye catches it easily.

85
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:36,760
Our job is to wind the coil so that those stripes stop dead.

86
00:10:38,720 --> 00:10:40,460
Good luck to everyone building.

87
00:10:43,340 --> 00:10:46,040
The schematic will be posted under the video.
